. Endothelin (ET)-1 is a polypeptide of 21 amino acids and contains two disulfide bonds located close to the N-terminus. ET-1 is believed to have an important role in a variety of physiological processes and contributes to the development of diseases such as atherosclerosis, hypertension, chronic heart failure, pulmonary hypertension, acute and chronic renal failure, etc (1-3). All of these effects are mediated through a receptor-ligand interaction. Two ET receptors, ET